bj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8740367293357849, "span": {"begin": 805, "end": 818}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:55894", "414325"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "defensins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9797577261924744, "span": {"begin": 873, "end": 882}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6285", "6271"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "S100 family proteins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9881224632263184, "span": {"begin": 888, "end": 908}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3933"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "lipocalin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9721977114677429, "span": {"begin": 910, "end": 919}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:820"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "LL37", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9963010549545288, "span": {"begin": 925, "end": 929}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:820"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "cathelicidin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.991926908493042, "span": {"begin": 930, "end": 942}}, {"id": ["CL:0000775"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neutrophil", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6795588731765747, "span": {"begin": 996, "end": 1006}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:50616"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-22", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9899441003799438, "span": {"begin": 1042, "end": 1047}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Th22 and Th17 cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9584721922874451, "span": {"begin": 1071, "end": 1090}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Th22", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8503743410110474, "span": {"begin": 1071, "end": 1075}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:50604", "27190"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IL-20 family members", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9787943959236145, "span": {"begin": 1104, "end": 1124}}, {"id": ["CL:0000312"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "keratinocyte", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8031489253044128, "span": {"begin": 1133, "end": 1145}}], "text": "IL-23 is important for differentiation and proliferation of Th17 cells. As a major source of IL-23, Tip-DC is present in the skin lesions of psoriatic patients and works to activate the Th17 pathway (Hansel et al. 2011).  Signaling through the heterodimeric IL-23 receptor (subunits of p19 and p40) of Th17 cells stimulates the production of proinflammatory keratinocyte cytokines that mediate the psoriatic response and induces the production of IL-17. Th17 cells are increased in the peripheral blood and lesion skin of psoriatic patients, and IL-17 and IL-22 produced from Th17 act on epidermal keratinocytes to cause inflammatory chemokines and hyperproliferation (Michelle A. et al. 2005).  IL-17A, which is highly expressed by Th17 cells, has a direct effect on the regulation of genes expressed by keratinocytes that are involved in innate immune defense, including defensins,8, 9 S100 family proteins, lipocalin, and LL37/cathelicidin, as well as a range of CXCL chemokines that regulate neutrophil trafficking (Gilliet et al. 2004). IL-22, which is expressed by Th22 and Th17 cells, and related IL-20 family members promote keratinocyte hyperproliferation and abnormal differentiation (Krueger et al. 2012).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:23:12 +0000 2026"}